-- Europe shares rise, yen falls on Putin Ukraine comments
-- By Blaise Robinson
-- Tue Mar 18, 2014 07:55AM EDT
-- None



PARIS, March 18 (Reuters) - European shares turned positive, the yen dipped and Bunds hit an intraday low on Tuesday after Russian President Vladimir Putin said it does not want to seize more of Ukraine after approving plans to make Crimea part of Russia.

"Don't believe those who try to frighten you with Russia and who scream that other regions will follow after Crimea," Putin said. "We do not want a partition of Ukraine, we do not need this." [ID:nL6N0MF2RX] At 1150 GMT, the FTSEurofirst 300 <.FTEU3> index of top  European shares was up 0.4 percent at 1,303.17 points. German Bund futures <FGBLc1> reversed gains to hit the day's low of 143.09, down 15 ticks from the previous close.